== Disciple
/* Cleric, Druid, Bard, Warlock */
You have faith in a deity, follow the teachings of a powerful patron, or see yourself as the herald of natural forces. 
You are a conduit for this outside power, or a student of it. 
Play this class to double down on a thematic character concept and tie it to the fantasy from the start. 

*Domains.* Choose two of the following elements that best reflect the nature of what you follow or worship. 
They are your two _domains_. 
For instance, a disciple of a goddess of harvests could choose Rest and Wild. 
A student of a bardic school could choose Bold and Lore. 

Bold - Awe, Passion. 
Arms - War, Authority. 
Magic - Magic, Strange. 
Fire - Zeal, Destruction. 
Hoax - Night, Dreams. 
Lore - Knowledge, Secrets. 
Rest - Healing, Death: Heal, deal damage to undead. 
Tinker - Craftsmanship, Civilization. 
Wild - Nature, Sea: Heal and damage mixed. 

*Mantras.*
Write 2 mantras that players can repeat or respond to, one per domain. Teach them to the other players. 

Tough. _When the going gets tough_: (targeted player) _The tough get going._
Magic. _Praise be to Jess_: (targeted player) _Matron of Magic and Tasteful Cupcakes._
Fire. _Fireball!_: (targeted player) _Taaa, ta ta, da ta da_
Arms. _Swords out for our Lord Aramde_: (other players thump their chests)

Any player-hero who responds gains Advantage on that test. 
You can say each mantra once, and must rest before you say it again. 

*Icon of Devotion.* 
Object you wield - a religious icon, a musical instrument, a sprig of mistletoe. It's not a weapon at all. 
When you wield it, reroll 1 and 2 on tests relevant to your domains. 


== Druid
This class may contain nuts. 
Seriously, if there are nut allergies at your table, substitute them with candy or play something else. 

Procure a bag of peanuts, cashews or other crunchy delight. 
If you can easily procure them each session, berries are also acceptable. 

You dispense blessings: metaphorical (advice) or physical (magical berries). 
Your nuts also count as threat tokens?
